        'tags'        => ['core-web-vitals', 'lcp', 'inp', 'cls', 'page-experience', 'performance'],
        'content'     => 'Core Web Vitals are Google\'s primary performance metrics and a confirmed ranking signal as of 2026. The three metrics and their thresholds are: (1) Largest Contentful Paint (LCP) measures loading performance. The target is under 2.5 seconds for the 75th percentile of page loads. LCP measures when the largest visible element (hero image, heading block, or video poster) finishes rendering. To optimize: use preload hints for critical images, serve images in WebP/AVIF format, implement a CDN, minimize render-blocking CSS/JS, and use server-side rendering or static generation where possible. (2) Interaction to Next Paint (INP) replaced First Input Delay (FID) in March 2024 as the responsiveness metric. INP measures the latency of all user interactions throughout the page lifecycle, not just the first. The threshold is under 200 milliseconds for a "good" score. Optimize by breaking long JavaScript tasks into smaller chunks using yield-to-main patterns, reducing DOM size below 1,500 nodes, minimizing third-party script impact, and using web workers for heavy computation. (3) Cumulative Layout Shift (CLS) measures visual stability. The target is a score below 0.1 for the 75th percentile. CLS penalizes unexpected layout shifts caused by images without dimensions, dynamically injected content, web fonts causing FOIT/FOUT, and late-loading ads. Always set explicit width and height on images and video elements, use CSS aspect-ratio or min-height for dynamic containers, preload custom fonts with font-display: optional, and reserve space for ad slots. Google uses field data from the Chrome User Experience Report (CrUX) collected over a rolling 28-day window. Lab tools like Lighthouse provide estimates, but real-user metrics are what count for ranking. Pages failing any single metric are classified as "poor" and may see reduced visibility in search results.',
