        'content'     => 'Google\'s Helpful Content system, integrated into the core ranking algorithm since March 2024, is a site-wide signal that classifies entire domains based on the proportion of helpful versus unhelpful content. A site with a significant amount of unhelpful content will see all its pages demoted, not just the low-quality ones. To comply, follow these principles: (1) Write for people first, not search engines. Content should satisfy the reader\'s intent completely without requiring them to search again. (2) Stay within your area of expertise. Do not publish content on unrelated topics solely to attract search traffic. A pet supplies store publishing cryptocurrency guides is a red flag. (3) Provide substantial value beyond what is already available. Aggregating or summarizing existing content without adding original insight, data, or perspective is classified as unhelpful. (4) Avoid producing content at scale without quality oversight. Mass-producing thin articles covering every possible keyword variation triggers the classifier. (5) Answer the question thoroughly. If your title promises "10 Best Laptops for Students 2026," the content must include genuine evaluations, not placeholders or affiliate-driven fluff. (6) Remove or improve existing unhelpful content. Audit your site for pages with high bounce rates and low dwell time. Either substantially improve them, consolidate them, or remove them with proper 301 redirects. (7) Avoid clickbait titles or misleading promises. If your title says "shocking results," the content must deliver something genuinely noteworthy. Recovery from a Helpful Content demotion is slow, typically taking 3 to 6 months after significant quality improvements are validated by Google\'s crawler. Prevention is far easier than recovery. Regularly audit content quality and prune underperforming pages.',
