        'content'     => 'Since July 2024, Google exclusively uses mobile-first indexing for all websites, with no exceptions or opt-outs. This means Google\'s crawler (Googlebot smartphone) uses the mobile version of your content for indexing and ranking. Key requirements: (1) Content parity: all content visible on the desktop version must be present and accessible on the mobile version. Content hidden behind tabs, accordions, or "read more" toggles is fully indexed but ensure it is present in the initial HTML response, not loaded via lazy JavaScript that Googlebot may not execute. (2) Structured data must be present on the mobile version. If your desktop page has Product schema but the mobile version does not, Google will not see it. Verify using the Rich Results Test with the mobile user agent. (3) Meta tags (title, description, robots) must be identical on mobile and desktop versions. Discrepancies cause indexing confusion. (4) Images and videos must be accessible on mobile with proper alt text and structured data. Use srcset for responsive images and ensure lazy-loaded images use the loading="lazy" attribute rather than JavaScript-only solutions that Googlebot may miss. (5) Internal links must work on mobile. If your mobile navigation omits links present in the desktop version, those pages lose internal link equity. (6) Page speed on mobile networks matters. Test with 4G throttling enabled, targeting LCP under 2.5 seconds on a mid-tier mobile device. (7) Touch targets must be at least 48x48 CSS pixels with at least 8 pixels of spacing to prevent accidental taps. (8) Font sizes should be a minimum of 16px for body text to avoid "text too small" flags. (9) Viewport must be configured correctly with meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1". Avoid user-scalable=no as it hurts accessibility. Use the Mobile-Friendly Test and Search Console\'s Mobile Usability report to identify issues.',
