        'content'     => 'Passage ranking, launched in February 2021 and refined through 2026, allows Google to rank individual passages within a page independently from the overall page relevance. This means a deeply buried paragraph answering a specific question can surface in search results even if the overall page covers a broader topic. How to optimize for passage ranking: (1) Use clear, descriptive subheadings (H2, H3) that mirror common search queries. Instead of "Our Approach," use "How to Fix a Leaking Kitchen Faucet" as a subheading. Each section should be a self-contained answer. (2) Structure content with the inverted pyramid model: lead each section with a concise, direct answer in 1-2 sentences, then expand with supporting details, examples, and data. This gives Google a clean passage to extract. (3) Target long-tail questions explicitly. Research "People Also Ask" queries for your topic and address each one in a dedicated section. Use the question as the subheading and provide a complete answer within the first 40-60 words of the section. (4) Maintain topical coherence within each passage. Do not mix multiple concepts in a single paragraph. One idea per passage makes extraction cleaner. (5) Use transition sentences between sections to maintain page flow while keeping individual passages self-sufficient. (6) Aim for passages of 100-200 words that thoroughly answer a single question. Passages that are too short may lack sufficient context; passages that are too long dilute the focused answer. (7) Do not rely solely on passage ranking as a strategy. The page still needs overall quality signals: strong internal links, proper schema markup, good page experience, and domain authority. Passage ranking helps surface good content that might otherwise be overlooked, but the page must meet baseline quality thresholds first. Monitor passage-level performance through Search Console by examining queries that drive traffic to specific page sections.',
