        'content'     => 'Product schema (schema.org/Product) is essential for ecommerce SEO, enabling rich results including price, availability, ratings, and product images in search results. As of 2026, Google supports enhanced product rich results with expanded properties. Required properties: name (product name, must match the visible page title), image (at least one high-quality image URL; Google recommends multiple images in an array), and either offers or review. For the Offer sub-object: price (numeric value), priceCurrency (ISO 4217 code like "USD"), and availability (use schema.org values: InStock, OutOfStock, PreOrder, BackOrder, Discontinued) are required. Recommended properties include: description (up to 5,000 characters, matching visible page description), brand (Brand object with name property), sku (Stock Keeping Unit), gtin/gtin13/gtin14/mpn (Global Trade Item Number or Manufacturer Part Number for product identification), aggregateRating (AggregateRating object with ratingValue and reviewCount), review (array of Review objects with author, datePublished, reviewRating), color, size, material, and productID. Important implementation details for Magento: (1) Generate JSON-LD in the head section, not Microdata in the body. JSON-LD is Google\'s preferred format and is easier to maintain. (2) Ensure price reflects the actual displayed price including any sale/special pricing. Use the Offer\'s priceValidUntil for sale prices. (3) Include multiple Offer objects for product variants (sizes, colors) with different SKUs and prices. (4) Set offers.url to the specific product URL. (5) Use offers.shippingDetails (OfferShippingDetails) and offers.hasMerchantReturnPolicy (MerchantReturnPolicy) for enhanced merchant listing experiences in Google Shopping. (6) Validate using Google\'s Rich Results Test at search.google.com/test/rich-results. Example: {"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"Product","name":"Wireless Headphones Pro","image":["https://example.com/p