        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'schema_markup',
        'title'       => 'Review and AggregateRating Schema',
        'tags'        => ['schema', 'review', 'rating', 'aggregate-rating', 'stars', 'rich-results'],
        'content'     => 'Review and AggregateRating schema enable star ratings and review snippets in search results, which increase CTR by 15-25%. Google displays review stars for products, recipes, books, courses, events, local businesses, and creative works, but not for self-serving entities (your own organization or website). AggregateRating properties: ratingValue (average rating, e.g., 4.5), bestRating (maximum possible, default 5), worstRating (minimum possible, default 1), ratingCount (total number of ratings), and reviewCount (total number of reviews with text). Individual Review properties: author (Person or Organization with name, required), datePublished (ISO 8601 date), reviewRating (Rating with ratingValue), reviewBody (the review text). Example Product with AggregateRating and Reviews: {"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"Product","name":"SEO Toolkit Pro","aggregateRating":{"@type":"AggregateRating","ratingValue":"4.7","bestRating":"5","ratingCount":"2847","reviewCount":"1523"},"review":[{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Jane Smith"},"datePublished":"2026-01-15","reviewRating":{"@type":"Rating","ratingValue":"5","bestRating":"5"},"reviewBody":"Excellent tool for managing technical SEO across multiple Magento sites."}]}. Critical rules: (1) Reviews must be from real users, not fabricated. Google actively penalizes fake review markup. (2) Rating values must match what is visibly displayed on the page. (3) Author must be a real person or organization, not "Anonymous" or "Admin." (4) Do not markup editorial reviews as user reviews. (5) For Magento, generate AggregateRating from the native review system and map each approved review to a Review object. (6) Keep reviewCount and ratingCount accurate and updated with each page render. (7) Do not use AggregateRating on category pages that list multiple products; apply it only to individual product pages.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'schema_local_business',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'schema_markup',
        'title'       => 'LocalBusiness Schema Markup',
        'tags'        => ['schema', 'local-business', 'local-seo', 'google-maps', 'json-ld'],
        'content'     => 'LocalBusiness schema (schema.org/LocalBusiness) is essential for businesses with physical locations, powering local search results, Google Maps integration, and the Knowledge Panel for local entities. Use the most specific subtype available: Restaurant, Store, MedicalClinic, AutoRepair, LegalService, FinancialService, etc. Required properties: name (official business name matching Google Business Profile), address (PostalAddress with streetAddress, addressLocality, addressRegion, postalCode, addressCountry), telephone. Strongly recommended properties: openingHoursSpecification (array of OpeningHoursSpecification with dayOfWeek, opens, closes in 24-hour format), geo (GeoCoordinates with latitude and longitude), url (website URL), image (array of business photos), priceRange (dollar signs "$$" or descriptive range), servesCuisine (for restaurants), areaServed, hasMap (Google Maps URL), sameAs (social media profiles and Google Business Profile URL). Example: {"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"Store","name":"TechGear Electronics","address":{"@type":"PostalAddress","streetAddress":"123 Commerce Blvd","addressLocality":"Austin","addressRegion":"TX","postalCode":"78701","addressCountry":"US"},"geo":{"@type":"GeoCoordinates","latitude":"30.2672","longitude":"-97.7431"},"telephone":"+1-512-555-0199","openingHoursSpecification":[{"@type":"OpeningHoursSpecification","dayOfWeek":["Monday","Tuesday","Wednesday","Thursday","Friday"],"opens":"09:00","closes":"18:00"},{"@type":"OpeningHoursSpecification","dayOfWeek":"Saturday","opens":"10:00","closes":"16:00"}],"priceRange":"$$","url":"https://www.techgear.com"}. Best practices: (1) Keep NAP (Name, Address, Phone) consistent with Google Business Profile and all directory listings. (2) Include openingHoursSpecification for every day, including closed days with opens and closes set to the same time. (3) For multi-location businesses, create separate LocalBusiness markup for each location on its dedicated page. (4) Combine with aggregateRating if you display reviews. (5) Use department property for businesses within larger organizations.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'schema_article',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'schema_markup',
        'title'       => 'Article and BlogPosting Schema',
        'tags'        => ['schema', 'article', 'blog', 'news', 'publishing', 'json-ld'],
        'content'     => 'Article schema (schema.org/Article) and its subtypes BlogPosting and NewsArticle enable Google to understand and feature your content in Top Stories, Google News, Discover, and Article rich results. Choose the right type: Article for general articles, NewsArticle for timely news content, BlogPosting for blog entries, ScholarlyArticle for academic papers, and TechArticle for technical documentation. Required properties: headline (article title, max 110 characters), image (array with at least one image, recommended 1200px wide minimum, aspect ratios 16:9, 4:3, or 1:1), datePublished (ISO 8601), author (Person or Organization with name and url). Recommended properties: dateModified (ISO 8601, triggers "Updated" label in search results), publisher (Organization with name and logo), description (up to 300 characters), mainEntityOfPage (URL of the article page), articleBody (full text, useful for Discover), wordCount, articleSection (category), keywords (array of relevant terms). Example: {"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"BlogPosting","headline":"Complete Guide to Magento SEO in 2026","image":["https://example.com/seo-guide-hero.jpg"],"datePublished":"2026-03-15T08:00:00+00:00","dateModified":"2026-04-01T12:00:00+00:00","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"John Expert","url":"https://example.com/author/john-expert","jobTitle":"SEO Director","sameAs":["https://linkedin.com/in/johnexpert"]},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"SEO Academy","logo":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://example.com/logo.png"}},"description":"Comprehensive 2026 guide covering technical SEO, content optimization, and schema markup for Magento stores.","mainEntityOfPage":"https://example.com/magento-seo-guide-2026"}. Best practices: (1) Always update dateModified when content is meaningfully changed. (2) Author must link to a real person or organization profile page. (3) Include multiple image sizes/ratios for different Google surfaces. (4) Ensure headline matches the visible H1 exactly. (5) For Google News eligibility, use NewsArticle and follow Google News content policies.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'schema_video',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'schema_markup',
        'title'       => 'VideoObject Schema Markup',
        'tags'        => ['schema', 'video', 'video-seo', 'youtube', 'rich-results', 'json-ld'],
        'content'     => 'VideoObject schema (schema.org/VideoObject) enables video rich results including thumbnails, duration, and key moments in search results. With video content driving increasingly larger share of search engagement in 2026, proper video schema is critical. Required properties: name (video title), description (video description), thumbnailUrl (URL to the video thumbnail image, minimum 160x90px, recommended 1920x1080px), uploadDate (ISO 8601 datetime), contentUrl (direct URL to the video file) or embedUrl (URL of the video player embed). Recommended properties: duration (ISO 8601 duration, e.g., "PT5M30S" for 5 minutes 30 seconds), interactionStatistic (for view count), expires (if the video has an expiration date), hasPart (array of Clip objects for key moments), publisher (Organization), author (Person or Organization), isFamilyFriendly (boolean), inLanguage, and transcript. Key moments with Clip objects: {"@type":"Clip","name":"Introduction to SEO","startOffset":0,"endOffset":45,"url":"https://example.com/video#t=0"},{"@type":"Clip","name":"Technical SEO Setup","startOffset":45,"endOffset":180,"url":"https://example.com/video#t=45"}. Full example: {"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"VideoObject","name":"Magento SEO Tutorial 2026","description":"Learn how to optimize your Magento store for Google in 2026","thumbnailUrl":"https://example.com/video-thumb.jpg","uploadDate":"2026-03-01T08:00:00+00:00","duration":"PT12M45S","contentUrl":"https://example.com/videos/magento-seo.mp4","embedUrl":"https://example.com/embed/magento-seo","interactionStatistic":{"@type":"InteractionCounter","interactionType":"https://schema.org/WatchAction","userInteractionCount":15400}}. Best practices: (1) Each page should only have one primary video with VideoObject markup. (2) The video must be publicly accessible, not behind a login. (3) Thumbnail must accurately represent the video content. (4) For YouTube-hosted videos, Google extracts metadata automatically, but adding VideoObject on your embedding page improves that page\'s ranking potential. (5) Use the Indexing API to notify Google of new video content quickly.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'schema_image',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'schema_markup',
        'title'       => 'ImageObject Schema Markup',
        'tags'        => ['schema', 'image', 'image-seo', 'visual-search', 'json-ld'],
        'content'     => 'ImageObject schema (schema.org/ImageObject) helps Google understand images beyond alt text, supporting Google Images ranking, visual search, and Google Lens integration. While Google can extract basic image information from HTML, explicit ImageObject schema provides richer context. Required properties: contentUrl (direct URL to the image file), if used standalone. When used as a property of another type (e.g., Product image), only the URL string is required. Recommended properties: name (image title), description (detailed image description), caption (visible caption text), width (in pixels), height (in pixels), encodingFormat (MIME type like "image/webp"), datePublished, author (photographer/creator as Person), copyrightHolder, license (URL to the license), acquireLicensePage (URL where the image can be licensed), creditText (attribution text). Example standalone ImageObject: {"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"ImageObject","contentUrl":"https://example.com/images/product-hero.webp","name":"Wireless Headphones Pro - Front View","description":"Front view of the Wireless Headphones Pro showing active noise cancellation controls","width":"1200","height":"800","encodingFormat":"image/webp","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Studio Photographer"},"copyrightHolder":{"@type":"Organization","name":"TechGear Inc"},"license":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","acquireLicensePage":"https://example.com/image-licensing"}. For ecommerce: (1) Include ImageObject markup for primary product images with detailed descriptions that include product attributes (color, size, material). (2) Use the representativeOfPage property (boolean true) for the hero/main image. (3) For products with multiple views, create an array of ImageObject entries. (4) Always serve images in modern formats (WebP with JPEG fallback, or AVIF) and declare the encodingFormat. (5) Image schema combined with proper alt text, filename optimization (descriptive-product-name.webp), and surrounding textual context creates the strongest image SEO signal. Google Images drives 20-25% of all Google search traffic, making image optimization a significant traffic opportunity.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'schema_webpage',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'schema_markup',
        'title'       => 'WebPage Schema Markup',
        'tags'        => ['schema', 'webpage', 'site-structure', 'sitelinks', 'json-ld'],
        'content'     => 'WebPage schema (schema.org/WebPage) and its subtypes provide Google with page-level metadata about the purpose and structure of individual pages. While not generating visible rich results, WebPage schema improves Google\'s understanding of your site architecture. Use specific subtypes: AboutPage (about us), ContactPage (contact), FAQPage (FAQ sections), CheckoutPage (checkout), CollectionPage (category/listing pages), ItemPage (individual product/article pages), ProfilePage (author/user profiles), SearchResultsPage (internal search results, mark as noindex), and WebPage for general pages. Key properties: name (page title), description (page description), url (canonical URL), datePublished, dateModified, inLanguage (BCP-47 code like "en-US"), isPartOf (the WebSite entity), breadcrumb (BreadcrumbList object), mainEntity (the primary entity described on the page), primaryImageOfPage (ImageObject), speakable (SpeakableSpecification for voice search, defining CSS selectors or XPaths of content suitable for text-to-speech), significantLink (array of important outgoing links), lastReviewed. Example with WebSite connection: {"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"ItemPage","name":"Wireless Headphones Pro","description":"Premium noise-cancelling wireless headphones","url":"https://example.com/wireless-headphones-pro","dateModified":"2026-03-15","inLanguage":"en-US","isPartOf":{"@type":"WebSite","name":"TechGear","url":"https://example.com","potentialAction":{"@type":"SearchAction","target":{"@type":"EntryPoint","urlTemplate":"https://example.com/search?q={search_term_string}"},"query-input":"required name=search_term_string"}},"breadcrumb":{"@type":"BreadcrumbList","itemListElement":[{"@type":"ListItem","position":1,"name":"Home","item":"https://example.com"},{"@type":"ListItem","position":2,"name":"Headphones","item":"https://example.com/headphones"}]}}. The WebSite entity with SearchAction enables the site-specific search box in Google results (sitelinks searchbox). Include the potentialAction on your homepage WebSite markup.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'schema_itemlist',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'schema_markup',
        'title'       => 'ItemList Schema for Product Listings',
        'tags'        => ['schema', 'itemlist', 'product-listing', 'category-page', 'carousel'],
        'content'     => 'ItemList schema (schema.org/ItemList) enables carousel-style rich results for product listings, recipe collections, course lists, and article indexes. This is particularly valuable for Magento category pages and search results pages. The ItemList contains itemListElement, an array of ListItem objects with position (integer starting at 1), url (link to the item page), and optionally item (embedded schema object). There are two implementation approaches: (1) Summary ItemList with URLs only (recommended for category pages): {"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"ItemList","itemListElement":[{"@type":"ListItem","position":1,"url":"https://example.com/product-1"},{"@type":"ListItem","position":2,"url":"https://example.com/product-2"},{"@type":"ListItem","position":3,"url":"https://example.com/product-3"}]}. Google will then crawl each URL and use the Product schema from those individual pages. (2) Detailed ItemList with embedded Product objects (for smaller lists of 5-10 items): {"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"ItemList","itemListElement":[{"@type":"ListItem","position":1,"item":{"@type":"Product","name":"Product One","image":"https://example.com/img1.jpg","offers":{"@type":"Offer","price":"29.99","priceCurrency":"USD"}}}]}. Additional properties: itemListOrder (ItemListOrderAscending, ItemListOrderDescending, or ItemListUnordered), numberOfItems (total count), name (list title). Best practices for Magento: (1) Use the summary approach for category pages with more than 10 products. (2) Include only the products visible on the current page, not all products in the category. (3) Position values must reflect the actual display order on the page. (4) For paginated category pages, start position at 1 on each page (not cumulative across pages). (5) Do not mix ItemList with individual Product schema on the same page for the same products. (6) For filtered/sorted results, update the ItemList order dynamically. (7) Maximum recommended items per ItemList is 30 for performance reasons.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'schema_offer',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'schema_markup',
        'title'       => 'Offer Schema for Pricing',
        'tags'        => ['schema', 'offer', 'pricing', 'ecommerce', 'availability', 'json-ld'],
        'content'     => 'Offer schema (schema.org/Offer) represents a commercial offer for a product or service and is critical for ecommerce rich results. It is typically used as the offers property within Product schema. Required properties: price (decimal number as string, e.g., "149.99"; use "0" for free items), priceCurrency (ISO 4217, e.g., "USD", "EUR", "GBP"). If the price varies, use AggregateOffer instead with lowPrice and highPrice. Required for rich results: availability (schema.org URL: InStock, OutOfStock, PreOrder, BackOrder, SoldOut, OnlineOnly, InStoreOnly, LimitedAvailability, Discontinued). Recommended properties: url (product URL), priceValidUntil (ISO 8601 date for sale prices; Google uses this to determine if price data is stale), itemCondition (NewCondition, RefurbishedCondition, UsedCondition, DamagedCondition), seller (Organization or Person), sku, mpn, gtin13. Shipping and returns properties (required for Google Merchant experience): shippingDetails (OfferShippingDetails with shippingRate as MonetaryAmount, deliveryTime as ShippingDeliveryTime with handlingTime and transitTime, and shippingDestination as DefinedRegion), hasMerchantReturnPolicy (MerchantReturnPolicy with returnPolicyCategory, merchantReturnDays, returnMethod, returnFees). AggregateOffer example for variable pricing: {"@type":"AggregateOffer","lowPrice":"29.99","highPrice":"89.99","priceCurrency":"USD","offerCount":"5","availability":"https://schema.org/InStock"}. Complete Offer with shipping: {"@type":"Offer","price":"149.99","priceCurrency":"USD","availability":"https://schema.org/InStock","itemCondition":"https://schema.org/NewCondition","priceValidUntil":"2026-12-31","shippingDetails":{"@type":"OfferShippingDetails","shippingRate":{"@type":"MonetaryAmount","value":"0","currency":"USD"},"shippingDestination":{"@type":"DefinedRegion","addressCountry":"US"},"deliveryTime":{"@type":"ShippingDeliveryTime","handlingTime":{"@type":"QuantitativeValue","minValue":"1","maxValue":"2","unitCode":"d"},"transitTime":{"@type":"QuantitativeValue","minValue":"3","maxValue":"5","unitCode":"d"}}},"hasMerchantReturnPolicy":{"@type":"MerchantReturnPolicy","returnPolicyCategory":"https://schema.org/MerchantReturnFiniteReturnWindow","merchantReturnDays":"30","returnMethod":"https://schema.org/ReturnByMail","returnFees":"https://schema.org/FreeReturn"}}. For Magento, dynamically generate Offer data from product price, stock status, and shipping/return configuration.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'schema_brand',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'schema_markup',
        'title'       => 'Brand Schema Markup',
        'tags'        => ['schema', 'brand', 'manufacturer', 'entity', 'json-ld'],
        'content'     => 'Brand schema (schema.org/Brand) establishes brand entity recognition and is used within Product schema to associate products with their manufacturers or brand names. Proper Brand markup helps Google build entity relationships in the Knowledge Graph, improving brand searches, product rich results, and Shopping integration. Properties: name (brand name, required), url (official brand website), logo (brand logo ImageObject or URL), description (brand description), slogan, sameAs (array of authoritative URLs: official website, Wikipedia page, Wikidata entry, social profiles), image, foundingDate, founder. Example within Product: {"@type":"Product","name":"UltraBoost Running Shoes","brand":{"@type":"Brand","name":"Adidas","url":"https://www.adidas.com","logo":"https://www.adidas.com/logo.png","sameAs":["https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adidas","https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q3895"]}}. For a standalone brand page: {"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"Brand","name":"Adidas","url":"https://www.adidas.com","logo":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.adidas.com/logo.png","width":"400","height":"400"},"description":"German multinational corporation specializing in athletic shoes, clothing, and accessories.","sameAs":["https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adidas","https://www.facebook.com/adidas","https://twitter.com/adidas","https://www.instagram.com/adidas"]}. Best practices for Magento: (1) Always include Brand markup within Product schema, even for house brands. Products without brand identification may not qualify for certain Google Shopping features. (2) Keep brand names consistent across all products. "Apple Inc." on one product and "Apple" on another creates entity fragmentation. Standardize brand names in your catalog. (3) For multi-brand stores, create dedicated brand landing pages with standalone Brand schema. (4) Link brand entities to Wikidata using the sameAs property for stronger Knowledge Graph connections. (5) Include the brand logo using ImageObject with explicit width and height for reliable rendering across Google surfaces. (6) If you manufacture your own products, use both Brand and Organization schema on your homepage to establish the relationship between your company entity and brand entity.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'schema_site_navigation',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'schema_markup',
        'title'       => 'SiteNavigationElement Schema',
        'tags'        => ['schema', 'navigation', 'sitelinks', 'menu', 'site-structure'],
        'content'     => 'SiteNavigationElement schema (schema.org/SiteNavigationElement) describes the main navigation structure of a website, helping Google understand site hierarchy and potentially influencing sitelink generation in search results. While Google generates sitelinks algorithmically, proper navigation markup provides clear signals about your most important pages. Implementation: SiteNavigationElement is applied to navigation elements, typically the main menu. Each navigation item is marked with name and url properties. Example using ItemList structure (recommended): {"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"ItemList","name":"Main Navigation","itemListElement":[{"@type":"SiteNavigationElement","position":1,"name":"Products","url":"https://example.com/products"},{"@type":"SiteNavigationElement","position":2,"name":"Categories","url":"https://example.com/categories"},{"@type":"SiteNavigationElement","position":3,"name":"Sale","url":"https://example.com/sale"},{"@type":"SiteNavigationElement","position":4,"name":"Blog","url":"https://example.com/blog"},{"@type":"SiteNavigationElement","position":5,"name":"About Us","url":"https://example.com/about"},{"@type":"SiteNavigationElement","position":6,"name":"Contact","url":"https://example.com/contact"}]}. For mega menus with subcategories, use nested structures: {"@type":"SiteNavigationElement","name":"Electronics","url":"https://example.com/electronics","hasPart":[{"@type":"SiteNavigationElement","name":"Laptops","url":"https://example.com/electronics/laptops"},{"@type":"SiteNavigationElement","name":"Phones","url":"https://example.com/electronics/phones"}]}. Best practices: (1) Include only your primary navigation items, typically 5-10 top-level entries. Do not map every link on the page. (2) Place this schema on all pages where the navigation is present (typically site-wide). (3) URLs must match the actual hrefs in your visible navigation. (4) Order should reflect the visual order of your navigation menu. (5) For Magento, dynamically generate from the category tree and CMS page menu configuration. (6) Combine with BreadcrumbList schema for comprehensive site structure markup. (7) Do not include user account links, cart links, or utility navigation in this schema. (8) Keep names concise and descriptive, matching the visible menu labels exactly.',
    ],

