    [
        'id'          => 'meta_title_optimization',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'meta_tags',
        'title'       => 'Title Tag Optimization - Character Count, Keyword Placement, CTR Triggers',
        'tags'        => ['title-tag', 'meta-title', 'ctr', 'serp', 'keyword-placement'],
        'content'     => 'The title tag remains the single most impactful on-page SEO element in 2026. It appears in the browser tab, search result headlines, and social media shares. Google may rewrite title tags that it deems unhelpful, but a well-optimized title is used as-is approximately 87% of the time. Character count: aim for 50-60 characters (approximately 580 pixels wide). Google truncates titles that exceed the display width with an ellipsis. Titles under 30 characters may be supplemented by Google with site name or other page content. Use a pixel-width checker rather than character count alone, as characters like "W" and "M" are wider than "i" and "l." Keyword placement: position your primary keyword as close to the beginning as possible. Eye-tracking studies show users scan the first 3-4 words most intensely. Format: "Primary Keyword - Secondary Keyword | Brand Name" or "Primary Keyword: Compelling Descriptor | Brand." CTR triggers that increase click-through rates: (1) Numbers and dates: "7 Best SEO Tools for 2026" outperforms "Best SEO Tools." Include the current year for time-sensitive topics. (2) Power words: "Complete," "Ultimate," "Proven," "Essential," "Free" drive curiosity. (3) Parenthetical clarifiers: "Guide (With Examples)" or "[2026 Updated]" increase CTR by 10-15%. (4) Questions: "How to Fix Crawl Errors?" matches search intent directly. (5) Negative framing: "10 SEO Mistakes That Kill Rankings" leverages loss aversion. Per-page-type formulas for Magento: Product pages: "[Product Name] - [Key Feature] | [Brand]" e.g., "Wireless Pro Headphones - Active Noise Cancelling | AudioTech." Category pages: "[Category] - Shop [Qualifier] | [Store]" e.g., "Wireless Headphones - Shop Premium Audio | TechGear." Blog posts: "[Number] [Adjective] [Topic] [Qualifier] ([Year])" e.g., "9 Proven Magento SEO Techniques for Higher Rankings (2026)." Avoid: keyword stuffing (repeating the same keyword multiple times), ALL CAPS (comes across as spammy), and misleading titles that do not match page content, which increases bounce rate and triggers Google title rewrites.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'meta_description_optimization',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'meta_tags',
        'title'       => 'Meta Description Optimization',
        'tags'        => ['meta-description', 'ctr', 'serp', 'snippet', 'search-results'],
        'content'     => 'Meta descriptions are not a direct ranking factor, but they significantly influence click-through rate (CTR), which indirectly affects rankings through user engagement signals. Google uses the meta description as the search result snippet approximately 63% of the time; in other cases, it pulls content from the page that better matches the query. Length: aim for 150-160 characters (approximately 920 pixels). Google occasionally displays longer descriptions (up to 300 characters) for certain queries, but 155 characters is the safe maximum. On mobile, descriptions are typically truncated to 120 characters, so front-load the most compelling information. Optimization principles: (1) Include the primary keyword naturally. Google bolds matching query terms in the description, visually drawing the user\'s eye. (2) Write a unique description for every page. Duplicate or missing meta descriptions across multiple pages is a common Magento issue. For stores with thousands of products, use dynamic templates: "[Product Name] - [Key Feature]. [Benefit statement]. Free shipping on orders over $[threshold]. Shop now at [Store]." (3) Include a clear call to action: "Shop now," "Learn more," "Compare prices," "Get free shipping," or "Read our expert review." (4) Add value propositions: free shipping thresholds, return policies, price match guarantees, or exclusive offers. (5) Use active voice and second person: "Find your perfect headphones" rather than "Headphones can be found." (6) For ecommerce, include: price range, availability, key product features, and trust signals (ratings, number of reviews). (7) Do not use quotation marks in meta descriptions as Google may truncate at the quote mark. Use single quotes or rephrase. (8) For category pages, describe the breadth of selection: "Browse 500+ wireless headphones from top brands. Compare features, read reviews, and find deals up to 40% off." (9) Test descriptions using SERP preview tools to see how they render on desktop and mobile before publishing.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'meta_keywords_2026',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'meta_tags',
        'title'       => 'Meta Keywords Tag - Relevance in 2026',
        'tags'        => ['meta-keywords', 'deprecated', 'legacy-seo', 'keyword-tag'],
        'content'     => 'The meta keywords tag (meta name="keywords") has been officially ignored by Google since September 2009 and remains completely irrelevant for Google rankings in 2026. Google\'s Gary Illyes, John Mueller, and Danny Sullivan have repeatedly confirmed that Google does not use the meta keywords tag in any way for web search ranking. Bing confirmed in 2014 that the meta keywords tag is used only as a spam signal, meaning its presence can potentially harm rankings on Bing if it contains spammy keyword stuffing. Yandex similarly does not use it for ranking. Should you include it? The recommendation for 2026 is to not include the meta keywords tag for the following reasons: (1) It provides zero SEO benefit on any major search engine. (2) It exposes your keyword strategy to competitors who can view your page source and see exactly which terms you are targeting. (3) It adds unnecessary bytes to the HTML document, however marginally affecting page load time. (4) It can trigger spam signals on Bing if overused. (5) It creates a maintenance burden with no return on investment. If your Magento installation has meta keywords fields in the admin, you can leave them empty or remove the functionality entirely through a module that strips the output. If a third-party extension or compliance requirement necessitates the tag, limit it to 3-5 highly relevant terms. What to focus on instead: invest time in optimizing title tags, meta descriptions, header tags, content quality, structured data, and internal linking, all of which have measurable impact on search visibility. For keyword targeting, use keywords naturally within the page content, title tag, H1, image alt text, and URL slug. Google\'s natural language processing is sophisticated enough to understand topical relevance without explicit keyword declarations.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'meta_robots_directives',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'meta_tags',
        'title'       => 'Robots Meta Directives - Complete Reference',
        'tags'        => ['robots', 'noindex', 'nofollow', 'meta-robots', 'crawl-control', 'max-snippet'],
        'content'     => 'The robots meta tag (meta name="robots") controls how search engines index and display your pages. In 2026, this remains the primary page-level crawl directive mechanism. Core directives: index (default, allow indexing), noindex (prevent indexing; page will be removed from search results within days to weeks of detection), follow (default, follow links on the page for crawling and link equity), nofollow (do not follow any links on the page; note this does not prevent indexing of linked pages via other paths), none (equivalent to noindex, nofollow). Display directives: max-snippet:[number] (maximum character length for text snippets; -1 means unlimited, 0 means no snippet), max-image-preview:[setting] (none, standard, or large; controls image preview size in results; large is required for Discover eligibility), max-video-preview:[number] (maximum seconds of video preview; -1 for unlimited). Additional directives: noarchive (prevent cached page display), noimageindex (prevent image indexing from this page), notranslate (prevent translation offering in results), nositelinkssearchbox (prevent sitelinks search box), unavailable_after:[date] (remove after specified date in RFC 850 format). Common Magento applications: (1) noindex customer account pages, checkout, cart, and search results pages: <meta name="robots" content="noindex, follow">. (2) Use max-image-preview:large on all content pages for Discover eligibility: <meta name="robots" content="index, follow, max-image-preview:large, max-snippet:-1, max-video-preview:-1">. (3) noindex filtered category pages with parameters to prevent index bloat: /category?color=red&size=large should be noindex, follow. (4) noindex paginated pages beyond page 1 (optional strategy): /category?p=2 can be noindex, follow. (5) Apply unavailable_after to time-limited promotion pages. Important: noindex and nofollow are directives, not suggestions. Google must obey them. However, Google must crawl the page to see the directive, so blocking the page in robots.txt prevents Google from seeing a noindex tag, potentially keeping the page indexed via external links.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'meta_canonical_url',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'meta_tags',
        'title'       => 'Canonical URL Best Practices',
        'tags'        => ['canonical', 'duplicate-content', 'url-normalization', 'link-rel-canonical'],
        'content'     => 'The canonical tag (link rel="canonical") tells search engines which URL is the authoritative version of a page when duplicate or near-duplicate content exists at multiple URLs. This is one of the most important technical SEO elements for Magento stores, which often generate the same content at many URLs. Implementation rules: (1) Every page must have a self-referencing canonical tag pointing to its own clean URL, even if no duplicates exist. This establishes the preferred URL format. (2) The canonical URL must be an absolute URL with protocol: <link rel="canonical" href="https://www.example.com/product-name" />. Never use relative URLs. (3) Canonical tags are hints, not directives. Google may ignore canonicals that conflict with other signals (sitemaps, internal links, redirects). Strengthen canonical signals by ensuring internal links point to the canonical URL. (4) Cross-domain canonicals are supported. If the same content appears on two different domains, the duplicate can canonical to the original. Common Magento duplicate content scenarios: (1) Products accessible via multiple category paths: /electronics/headphones/product-name and /sale/product-name. Both should canonical to the clean URL: /product-name. (2) URL parameters for tracking, sorting, or filtering: /category?utm_source=email, /category?sort=price. Canonical should point to the parameter-free URL. (3) HTTP vs HTTPS and www vs non-www: all versions must resolve to one canonical format. (4) Trailing slashes: choose with or without and be consistent. (5) Pagination: page 1 of a category (/category?p=1) should canonical to /category (without the parameter). Pages 2+ should self-canonical to their own paginated URL, not to page 1. (6) Faceted navigation: /category?color=red should canonical to /category unless the filtered page has unique SEO value. Common mistakes to avoid: (1) Canonicalizing to a 404 or redirect URL. (2) Canonicalizing paginated pages to page 1 (this hides pages 2+ content from Google). (3) Conflicting canonical and noindex on the same page. (4) Chains of canonicals (A canonicals to B, B canonicals to C). Always canonical directly to the final target. (5) Using canonical to resolve fundamentally different content.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'meta_hreflang',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'meta_tags',
        'title'       => 'Hreflang Implementation',
        'tags'        => ['hreflang', 'international-seo', 'multilingual', 'localization', 'language'],
        'content'     => 'Hreflang annotations (link rel="alternate" hreflang="x") tell Google which language and regional version of a page to show users based on their language and location. This prevents duplicate content issues across international versions and ensures the correct page appears in each country\'s search results. Implementation methods (choose one): (1) HTML link tags in the head section (recommended for up to 20 language versions): <link rel="alternate" hreflang="en-us" href="https://example.com/en-us/product" /><link rel="alternate" hreflang="en-gb" href="https://example.co.uk/product" /><link rel="alternate" hreflang="x-default" href="https://example.com/product" />. (2) HTTP headers (for non-HTML files like PDFs): Link: <https://example.com/en/file.pdf>; rel="alternate"; hreflang="en". (3) XML sitemap (recommended for large sites with many language versions): <url><loc>https://example.com/en/product</loc><xhtml:link rel="alternate" hreflang="en" href="https://example.com/en/product"/><xhtml:link rel="alternate" hreflang="de" href="https://example.com/de/product"/></url>. Critical rules: (1) Hreflang must be reciprocal. If page A references page B, page B must reference page A. Non-reciprocal annotations are ignored. (2) Always include a self-referencing hreflang for the current page. (3) Include x-default for the fallback page shown to users who do not match any specific language/region. (4) Use ISO 639-1 language codes and optionally ISO 3166-1 Alpha 2 country codes: "en" (English, any region), "en-us" (English, United States), "en-gb" (English, United Kingdom), "pt-br" (Portuguese, Brazil). (5) The language code is case-insensitive but conventionally lowercase. (6) All referenced URLs must return 200 status, not redirect. (7) All referenced pages must have their own canonical tag pointing to themselves, not to another language version. For Magento multistore: configure hreflang based on store view language and website scope. Map each store view to its hreflang code. Generate annotations dynamically on every page using the product/category/CMS page URL key for each store view. Verify with Google Search Console\'s International Targeting report.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'meta_open_graph',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'meta_tags',
        'title'       => 'Open Graph Meta Tags - All Properties',
        'tags'        => ['open-graph', 'og-tags', 'social-media', 'facebook', 'linkedin', 'sharing'],
        'content'     => 'Open Graph (OG) meta tags control how your pages appear when shared on social media platforms including Facebook, LinkedIn, Pinterest, Discord, Slack, and messaging apps. While not a direct Google ranking factor, social sharing drives traffic and brand signals that indirectly support SEO. Required properties: og:title (sharing title, 60-90 characters; can differ from the SEO title tag to be more engaging for social audiences), og:description (sharing description, 150-200 characters), og:image (image URL, minimum 1200x630px for optimal display, 1.91:1 aspect ratio; must be an absolute URL), og:url (canonical URL of the page), og:type (website, article, product, profile, video.movie, music.album, etc.). Article-specific properties: article:published_time (ISO 8601), article:modified_time, article:author (URL to author profile), article:section (category), article:tag (topic tags). Product-specific properties: product:price:amount, product:price:currency, product:availability (instock, oos, pending), product:condition, product:retailer_item_id, product:brand. Additional recommended properties: og:site_name (your site/store name), og:locale (language_TERRITORY, e.g., "en_US"), og:locale:alternate (alternate locales for international pages), og:image:width and og:image:height (prevents rescraping to determine dimensions), og:image:alt (alt text for the OG image), og:video (video URL for video content). Example for a Magento product page: <meta property="og:type" content="product" /><meta property="og:title" content="Wireless Pro Headphones - Premium Audio" /><meta property="og:description" content="Experience crystal-clear sound with active noise cancellation. Free shipping on orders over $50." /><meta property="og:image" content="https://example.com/media/catalog/product/headphones-hero.jpg" /><meta property="og:image:width" content="1200" /><meta property="og:image:height" content="630" /><meta property="og:url" content="https://example.com/wireless-pro-headphones" /><meta property="og:site_name" content="TechGear" /><meta property="product:price:amount" content="149.99" /><meta property="product:price:currency" content="USD" /><meta property="product:availability" content="instock" />. Validate using Facebook\'s Sharing Debugger (developers.facebook.com/tools/debug/) and LinkedIn\'s Post Inspector (linkedin.com/post-inspector/). Use unique, compelling OG images for important pages rather than relying on auto-selected product thumbnails.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'meta_twitter_cards',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'meta_tags',
        'title'       => 'Twitter Card Meta Tags',
        'tags'        => ['twitter-cards', 'x-cards', 'social-media', 'twitter', 'sharing'],
        'content'     => 'Twitter Card meta tags (now X Cards following the platform rebrand) control how your content appears when shared on Twitter/X. Twitter Cards significantly increase engagement compared to plain text links. There are four card types: (1) summary: small square image with title and description. Use for general pages, articles, and blog posts. (2) summary_large_image: large rectangular image above title and description. Use for visual content, product pages, and feature articles. This is the most commonly used and recommended type. (3) player: for video or audio playback directly in the timeline. Requires application approval from Twitter. (4) app: for mobile application promotion with direct download links. Required properties: twitter:card (card type: "summary" or "summary_large_image"), twitter:title (up to 70 characters), twitter:description (up to 200 characters). Recommended properties: twitter:image (image URL; for summary: minimum 144x144px, max 4096x4096px; for summary_large_image: minimum 300x157px, recommended 1200x628px, max 4096x4096px, under 5MB), twitter:image:alt (image alt text, max 420 characters), twitter:site (@username of the website account), twitter:creator (@username of the content author). Example for an ecommerce product: <meta name="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image" /><meta name="twitter:site" content="@techgearstore" /><meta name="twitter:title" content="Wireless Pro Headphones - Now 30% Off" /><meta name="twitter:description" content="Premium noise-cancelling headphones with 40hr battery. Free 2-day shipping. Limited time offer." /><meta name="twitter:image" content="https://example.com/media/catalog/product/headphones-social.jpg" /><meta name="twitter:image:alt" content="Wireless Pro Headphones in midnight blue" />. Important notes: (1) Twitter falls back to Open Graph tags if Twitter Card tags are missing. If you have OG tags, you only need twitter:card to override the card type. (2) Images are cached aggressively. Use Twitter Card Validator (cards-dev.twitter.com/validator) to force refresh after changes. (3) For Magento, generate twitter:card, twitter:site, and twitter:image on all pages. Let twitter:title and twitter:description fall back to og:title and og:description. (4) Create specific social images for high-value pages with branded overlays and compelling visuals.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'meta_viewport',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'meta_tags',
        'title'       => 'Viewport Meta Tag Configuration',
        'tags'        => ['viewport', 'responsive-design', 'mobile', 'device-width', 'accessibility'],
        'content'     => 'The viewport meta tag controls how a page is displayed on mobile devices and is essential for mobile-first indexing. Without it, mobile browsers render the page at a desktop width (typically 980px) and scale it down, resulting in tiny text and failed mobile-friendliness tests. The correct implementation is: <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">. This tells the browser to set the viewport width to match the device screen width and start at 1x zoom. Property breakdown: width=device-width sets the viewport width to the device\'s screen width in CSS pixels (e.g., 375px for iPhone, 412px for Pixel). initial-scale=1 sets the initial zoom level to 100%. Properties to avoid: (1) maximum-scale=1 or user-scalable=no. These prevent users from zooming in, which is an accessibility violation (WCAG 2.1 Success Criterion 1.4.4) and may result in Lighthouse/PageSpeed accessibility penalties. Users with low vision depend on pinch-to-zoom. Some browsers now ignore user-scalable=no entirely. (2) minimum-scale: rarely needed and can cause usability issues. (3) Fixed width values like width=1024: forces a specific viewport width, breaking responsive design. Common mistakes in Magento: (1) Missing the viewport tag entirely on custom themes. Verify it appears in the head section of every page. (2) Placing the viewport tag after large CSS files, causing a brief flash of incorrectly scaled content. Position it as one of the first meta tags in the head. (3) Multiple viewport tags from conflicting theme extensions. Only one viewport tag should exist. (4) Using viewport-fit=cover without proper safe-area-inset handling for devices with notches (iPhone). If using viewport-fit=cover, add CSS: padding: env(safe-area-inset-top) env(safe-area-inset-right) env(safe-area-inset-bottom) env(safe-area-inset-left). Testing: Use Chrome DevTools Device Mode to test viewport behavior across multiple device sizes. Verify with Google\'s Mobile-Friendly Test and Search Console\'s Mobile Usability report.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'meta_csp_headers',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'meta_tags',
        'title'       => 'Content-Security-Policy Headers for SEO',
        'tags'        => ['csp', 'security-headers', 'content-security-policy', 'https', 'trust'],
        'content'     => 'Content-Security-Policy (CSP) is an HTTP header (or meta tag) that controls which resources the browser is allowed to load, preventing cross-site scripting (XSS), clickjacking, and code injection attacks. While CSP does not directly affect SEO rankings, it contributes to site security, which impacts trust signals, safe browsing status, and user experience. Implementation via HTTP header (preferred): Content-Security-Policy: default-src \'self\'; script-src \'self\' https://www.googletagmanager.com https://www.google-analytics.com; style-src \'self\' \'unsafe-inline\' https://fonts.googleapis.com; img-src \'self\' data: https:; font-src \'self\' https://fonts.gstatic.com; connect-src \'self\' https://www.google-analytics.com; frame-src https://www.youtube.com https://www.google.com; base-uri \'self\'; form-action \'self\'. Or via meta tag: <meta http-equiv="Content-Security-Policy" content="default-src \'self\'; ...">. Key directives: default-src (fallback for all resource types), script-src (JavaScript sources), style-src (CSS sources), img-src (image sources), font-src (font sources), connect-src (XHR/fetch/WebSocket targets), frame-src (iframe sources), media-src (audio/video sources), base-uri (restricts base tag targets), form-action (restricts form submission targets), frame-ancestors (prevents clickjacking, replaces X-Frame-Options). SEO-relevant considerations: (1) Overly restrictive CSP can break Googlebot rendering. Ensure Google\'s domains are whitelisted: googletagmanager.com, google-analytics.com, google.com, gstatic.com, googleapis.com. (2) Test CSP in report-only mode first: Content-Security-Policy-Report-Only with a report-uri directive to catch violations without breaking functionality. (3) Magento requires unsafe-inline for some core styles and scripts. Use nonces or hashes for stricter CSP. (4) Other security headers to implement alongside CSP: X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff, X-Frame-Options: SAMEORIGIN, Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains (HSTS), Referrer-Policy: strict-origin-when-cross-origin, Permissions-Policy (restrict camera, microphone, geolocation access). These headers collectively improve your security posture, protect against safe browsing flags, and support HTTPS trust signals.',
    ],

