    [
        'id'          => 'tech_xml_sitemap',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'technical_seo',
        'title'       => 'XML Sitemap Best Practices 2026',
        'tags'        => ['sitemap', 'xml-sitemap', 'crawling', 'indexing', 'google-search-console'],
        'content'     => 'XML sitemaps help search engines discover and prioritize your pages for crawling. While Google can find pages through links, sitemaps are critical for large ecommerce sites with thousands of pages. Sitemap protocol requirements: (1) Maximum 50,000 URLs per sitemap file and maximum 50MB uncompressed file size. For large Magento stores, use a sitemap index file referencing multiple sitemap files. (2) Submit the sitemap index URL in Google Search Console and reference it in robots.txt: Sitemap: https://example.com/sitemap.xml. (3) Use lastmod only when the page content has genuinely changed. Do not set all dates to today or use automated timestamps that update without content changes. Google has confirmed that inaccurate lastmod values cause it to ignore the timestamp entirely. (4) The priority and changefreq tags are ignored by Google in 2026. You can omit them to reduce file size. Bing still considers changefreq, so include it if Bing traffic matters. Content rules: (1) Include only canonical, indexable URLs (200 status, no noindex, matching the canonical tag). (2) Exclude: noindex pages, redirected URLs, paginated pages (optional), filtered/sorted category URLs, customer account pages, checkout pages, and internal search results. (3) Include: all product pages (in stock and out of stock if they have SEO value), category pages, CMS pages, blog posts, and brand pages. (4) Use separate sitemaps for different content types: sitemap-products.xml, sitemap-categories.xml, sitemap-cms.xml, sitemap-images.xml. This makes monitoring in Search Console easier. Image sitemaps: extend the product sitemap with image:image elements including image:loc, image:title, and image:caption. This helps Google discover product images that may be loaded via JavaScript. Video sitemaps: use the video: namespace for pages with embedded video content. Monitoring: compare the number of URLs in your sitemap with the "Indexed" count in Search Console. A large gap indicates quality or technical issues. Regenerate sitemaps automatically after product/category changes and submit for reindexing via the Search Console API or Indexing API for eligible content types.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'tech_robots_txt',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'technical_seo',
        'title'       => 'robots.txt Optimization',
        'tags'        => ['robots-txt', 'crawl-budget', 'crawling', 'user-agent', 'disallow'],
        'content'     => 'The robots.txt file controls which URLs search engine crawlers can access. It is a crawl directive, not an indexing directive. Blocking a URL in robots.txt does not remove it from search results if external links point to it. The file must be at the root domain: https://example.com/robots.txt. Syntax: User-agent specifies which crawler the rules apply to. Use * for all crawlers or specific names like Googlebot, Bingbot, GPTBot. Disallow prevents crawling of matched URL paths. Allow overrides Disallow for specific paths within a blocked directory. Sitemap declares sitemap location. Recommended robots.txt for Magento 2: User-agent: * Disallow: /checkout/ Disallow: /customer/ Disallow: /wishlist/ Disallow: /catalogsearch/ Disallow: /catalog/product_compare/ Disallow: /sendfriend/ Disallow: /review/product/list/ Disallow: /newsletter/ Disallow: /paypal/ Disallow: /admin/ Disallow: /*?SID= Disallow: /*?___store= Disallow: /*?___from_store= Allow: /media/ Allow: /static/ Sitemap: https://example.com/sitemap.xml. Important considerations: (1) Do not block CSS and JavaScript files. Googlebot must render pages, and blocking render resources causes mobile-friendliness and indexing failures. (2) Do not use robots.txt to handle duplicate content. Use canonical tags and noindex instead. Disallowed pages can still be indexed via external links, appearing in results with no snippet. (3) For faceted navigation, do not block filtered URLs if you want Google to follow links on those pages. Instead use noindex meta tags on the filtered pages themselves. (4) Block AI training crawlers if desired: User-agent: GPTBot Disallow: / User-agent: CCBot Disallow: / User-agent: anthropic-ai Disallow: /. (5) The crawl-delay directive is respected by Bing but ignored by Google. Use Search Console\'s crawl rate settings for Google. (6) Test your robots.txt using Google Search Console\'s robots.txt Tester. (7) robots.txt is cached by Google for up to 24 hours. Changes do not take immediate effect. (8) A missing or 500-error robots.txt causes Google to assume all crawling is allowed. A 429 or persistent 5xx causes Google to pause crawling entirely.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'tech_structured_data_testing',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'technical_seo',
        'title'       => 'Structured Data Testing and Validation',
        'tags'        => ['structured-data', 'testing', 'validation', 'rich-results', 'schema-errors'],
        'content'     => 'Validating structured data is essential to ensure rich results eligibility and avoid penalties for incorrect markup. Use multiple testing tools at different stages. Primary testing tools: (1) Google Rich Results Test (search.google.com/test/rich-results): tests whether a page is eligible for rich results. Shows which rich result types are detected, any errors or warnings, and a rendered preview. Supports both URL testing and code snippet testing. This is the definitive test for Google compatibility. (2) Schema.org Validator (validator.schema.org): validates markup against the full schema.org vocabulary. More strict than Google\'s tool, as it checks all properties against schema.org definitions, not just Google-supported ones. Use this to ensure complete and correct schema implementation. (3) Google Search Console Rich Results report: shows aggregate data about rich results across your entire site, including valid items, items with warnings, and items with errors. Check weekly for newly detected issues. (4) Google Search Console URL Inspection Tool: test individual URLs for indexing status, detected structured data, and rich result eligibility. Common errors and fixes: (1) "Missing field" errors: add the required property. Google\'s requirements may differ from schema.org\'s requirements. (2) "Invalid value" errors: typically caused by wrong data types (string instead of number for price) or invalid URLs. (3) "Array expected" errors: some properties require arrays even for single values (e.g., Product image). (4) Mismatch between structured data and visible content: ensure schema values match what users see on the page. Google may issue manual actions for deceptive structured data. Testing workflow for Magento: (1) During development: test code snippets in the Rich Results Test. (2) After deployment: validate sample URLs from each page type (product, category, CMS, blog). (3) Ongoing: monitor Search Console Rich Results report for site-wide errors. (4) Automated: integrate schema validation into CI/CD pipelines using the Schema.org Validator API or custom validation scripts that check JSON-LD output against expected patterns. (5) Spot-check: after Magento updates or extension installations, re-test representative pages as theme changes can break structured data output.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'tech_page_speed',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'technical_seo',
        'title'       => 'Page Speed Optimization Techniques',
        'tags'        => ['page-speed', 'performance', 'core-web-vitals', 'loading', 'optimization'],
        'content'     => 'Page speed is a confirmed ranking factor through Core Web Vitals. Target: LCP under 2.5s, INP under 200ms, CLS under 0.1 on real user devices. Optimization techniques grouped by impact: Server-side optimizations (high impact): (1) Enable full page caching (Varnish for Magento 2). Cached pages should serve in under 200ms Time to First Byte (TTFB). (2) Use a CDN (Cloudflare, Fastly, AWS CloudFront) to serve assets from edge locations. Configure the CDN to cache static assets for 1 year with hashed filenames for cache busting. (3) Enable Gzip or Brotli compression. Brotli provides 15-20% better compression than Gzip for text-based assets. (4) Implement HTTP/2 or HTTP/3 for multiplexed connections, eliminating the need for domain sharding. (5) Use server-side rendering or edge-side rendering for critical above-the-fold content. Critical rendering path (high impact): (1) Inline critical CSS (the CSS needed for above-the-fold content) directly in the HTML head. Load remaining CSS asynchronously using rel="preload" as="style" with onload handler. (2) Defer non-critical JavaScript with defer or async attributes. Move analytics, chat widgets, and social scripts to load after the main content. (3) Preload critical resources: <link rel="preload" as="image" href="hero.webp"> for LCP images, <link rel="preload" as="font" href="font.woff2" crossorigin> for web fonts. (4) Remove unused CSS and JavaScript. Audit with Chrome DevTools Coverage tab. Magento themes often load 200KB+ of unused CSS. Asset optimization (medium impact): (1) Minify CSS, JavaScript, and HTML. Enable Magento\'s built-in minification and bundling. (2) Implement tree shaking to eliminate unused JavaScript modules. (3) Use modern JavaScript (ES modules) with module/nomodule pattern for legacy browser fallback. Image optimization (high impact for LCP): (1) Serve images in WebP (90% browser support) or AVIF (80% support) format. (2) Implement responsive images with srcset and sizes attributes. (3) Lazy load below-the-fold images with loading="lazy". Never lazy load the LCP image. (4) Set explicit width and height on all image elements to prevent CLS. (5) Use CSS aspect-ratio for responsive image containers. Third-party scripts (medium impact for INP): (1) Load third-party scripts in a web worker using Partytown or similar. (2) Delay non-essential third-party scripts until user interaction. (3) Self-host critical third-party resources (fonts, analytics libraries) to eliminate DNS lookup and connection overhead.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'tech_image_optimization',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'technical_seo',
        'title'       => 'Image Optimization - WebP, AVIF, Lazy Loading, Srcset',
        'tags'        => ['images', 'webp', 'avif', 'lazy-loading', 'srcset', 'responsive-images'],
        'content'     => 'Images account for 40-60% of total page weight on ecommerce sites. Proper optimization directly impacts LCP, bandwidth usage, and user experience. Modern formats: (1) WebP offers 25-35% smaller files than JPEG at equivalent quality and supports transparency (replacing PNG). Browser support is 97%+ in 2026. Use as the default format for all product images. (2) AVIF offers 40-50% smaller files than JPEG with superior quality. Browser support is approximately 92% in 2026 (Chrome, Firefox, Safari 16.4+). Use as the preferred format with WebP fallback. Implementation with picture element: <picture><source srcset="image.avif" type="image/avif"><source srcset="image.webp" type="image/webp"><img src="image.jpg" alt="Descriptive alt text" width="800" height="600" loading="lazy"></picture>. Responsive images with srcset: use srcset for resolution switching and sizes for viewport-based selection. Example: <img srcset="product-400w.webp 400w, product-800w.webp 800w, product-1200w.webp 1200w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 400px, (max-width: 1024px) 800px, 1200px" src="product-800w.webp" alt="Product Name" width="800" height="600" loading="lazy">. This lets the browser choose the optimal image size based on viewport width and device pixel ratio. Lazy loading: add loading="lazy" to all images below the fold. Critical rule: never lazy load the LCP image (typically the hero image or first product image). For the LCP image, add loading="eager" (default) and fetchpriority="high" to prioritize its download. For Magento: (1) Generate multiple image sizes during product image upload using resize operations. Create thumbnails (200px), listing images (400px), detail images (800px), and zoom images (1200px). (2) Convert to WebP/AVIF during generation using GD or Imagick. Hyva theme supports native lazy loading. (3) Set explicit width and height on every img element to prevent CLS. Magento\'s image helper provides dimensions. (4) Use descriptive alt text that includes the product name, key attributes, and context. "Wireless Pro Headphones in midnight blue on desk" is better than "headphones" or "IMG_4521." (5) Optimize file names: wireless-pro-headphones-midnight-blue.webp rather than product_123_1.webp. (6) Implement image CDN services (Cloudinary, imgix, Fastly Image Optimizer) for on-the-fly format conversion, resizing, and quality optimization.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'tech_javascript_seo',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'technical_seo',
        'title'       => 'JavaScript Rendering and SEO',
        'tags'        => ['javascript', 'rendering', 'spa', 'ssr', 'googlebot', 'js-seo'],
        'content'     => 'Google renders JavaScript using an evergreen Chromium-based renderer (Web Rendering Service, WRS), but JavaScript-dependent content faces crawling delays, rendering failures, and indexing challenges. In 2026, Google\'s renderer supports modern JavaScript (ES2022+), but rendering is a separate queue from crawling, introducing delays of seconds to days between initial crawl and full render. Key challenges: (1) Two-wave indexing: Google first crawls the raw HTML (wave 1), then renders the JavaScript later (wave 2). Content only available after JavaScript execution may take significantly longer to be indexed. (2) Rendering resources: Google must fetch all CSS, JS, and API endpoints to render a page. If any resource is blocked (robots.txt, server errors, timeouts), rendering fails partially or completely. (3) Client-side routing in SPAs: Google can follow links in client-side routed applications, but hash-based routing (#/page) is not crawled. Use History API (pushState) with clean URLs. (4) Dynamic content loading: content loaded on scroll, click, or after a timeout may not be rendered by Google. Google does not scroll, click, or wait for arbitrary timeouts. Best practices: (1) Server-side rendering (SSR) is the gold standard. Render complete HTML on the server and hydrate on the client. All critical content (product details, descriptions, reviews, structured data) should be in the initial HTML response. (2) If SSR is not possible, implement dynamic rendering: serve pre-rendered HTML to bot user agents and client-rendered content to users. Google officially supports this approach but considers it a workaround, not a long-term solution. (3) For Hyva/Magento: Hyva theme uses Alpine.js with server-rendered HTML, which is SEO-friendly by default. Ensure product data, reviews, and pricing are in the initial HTML, not loaded via subsequent API calls. (4) Test JavaScript rendering: use Google Search Console\'s URL Inspection Tool "View Tested Page" to see the rendered HTML. Compare with the live page to identify content gaps. (5) Ensure JSON-LD structured data is present in the initial HTML or rendered during the JavaScript execution phase. Google processes JSON-LD after rendering. (6) Avoid rendering-dependent redirects (JavaScript-based redirects). Use server-side 301/302 redirects.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'tech_internal_linking',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'technical_seo',
        'title'       => 'Internal Linking Strategies',
        'tags'        => ['internal-links', 'link-equity', 'site-structure', 'anchor-text', 'navigation'],
        'content'     => 'Internal linking distributes page authority (PageRank) throughout your site, establishes topical relationships, and guides both users and crawlers to important content. In 2026, internal linking remains one of the most controllable and impactful SEO levers. Core principles: (1) Flat site architecture: important pages should be reachable within 3 clicks from the homepage. For Magento stores, this means: Homepage > Category > Subcategory > Product (3 levels). Products deeper than 4 levels receive significantly less crawl frequency and link equity. (2) Descriptive anchor text: use keyword-rich, descriptive anchor text for internal links. "Wireless headphones" is better than "click here" or "learn more." Unlike external links, there is no over-optimization penalty for internal anchor text. Use your target keywords. (3) Link from high-authority pages to important target pages. Your homepage, popular blog posts, and top-ranking category pages have the most authority to distribute. Add contextual links from these pages to priority products or categories. (4) Contextual links within body content pass more relevance than navigation links. A link from a blog post about "best wireless headphones 2026" to your wireless headphones category page carries topical relevance that a nav link does not. Magento-specific strategies: (1) Related products, upsells, and cross-sells are internal links. Configure them strategically based on SEO priority, not just conversion potential. (2) Category descriptions should include 2-3 contextual links to key subcategories or featured products. (3) Blog content should link to relevant product and category pages. A buying guide should link to every product it mentions. (4) Breadcrumb links provide hierarchical internal linking on every page. Ensure breadcrumbs are HTML links, not JavaScript-only. (5) Pagination links (prev/next) distribute link equity through category pages. Do not nofollow pagination links. (6) Footer links to important category pages provide site-wide link equity, but limit to 10-15 key pages. Excessive footer links dilute value. (7) Orphan page audit: use Screaming Frog or Sitebulb to find pages with no internal links pointing to them. Every indexable page should have at least one internal link. (8) Fix broken internal links quarterly. 404-ing internal links waste crawl budget and link equity.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'tech_url_structure',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'technical_seo',
        'title'       => 'URL Structure Optimization',
        'tags'        => ['url-structure', 'url-optimization', 'slugs', 'clean-urls', 'hierarchy'],
        'content'     => 'URL structure affects crawlability, user experience, CTR in search results, and provides a minor ranking signal. In 2026, clean and descriptive URLs remain a best practice even as Google\'s ability to interpret messy URLs has improved. Principles: (1) Keep URLs short and descriptive: https://example.com/wireless-headphones/pro-model is better than https://example.com/catalog/category/id/42/product/id/1847. Aim for under 75 characters. Studies show CTR decreases with URL length. (2) Use hyphens (-) to separate words, not underscores (_), spaces (%20), or camelCase. Google treats hyphens as word separators. (3) Use lowercase letters exclusively. URLs are case-sensitive, and mixed case creates duplicate content risk. Configure your server to redirect uppercase URLs to lowercase. (4) Include the target keyword in the URL slug. /wireless-noise-cancelling-headphones ranks marginally better than /product-sku-wh2026 for "wireless noise cancelling headphones." (5) Avoid URL parameters for content variations when possible. /headphones/wireless is better than /headphones?type=wireless for pages that should be indexed. (6) Remove unnecessary directory levels. /shop/catalog/electronics/audio/headphones/wireless/product is too deep. /wireless-headphones/product is sufficient. (7) Use trailing slashes consistently. Choose either /category/ or /category and enforce it with redirects. Mixing creates duplicate content. Magento-specific URL configuration: (1) Set "Use Categories Path for Product URLs" to "No" in Stores > Configuration > Catalog > Search Engine Optimization. This creates flat product URLs (/product-name) instead of /category/subcategory/product-name, preventing duplicate URLs when products are in multiple categories. (2) Set URL suffix to blank or "/" consistently for both category and product pages. Avoid .html suffix as it provides no SEO benefit and adds unnecessary characters. (3) Configure URL rewrites to automatically generate clean URLs from product names. (4) Remove store codes from URLs when not needed for multilingual. (5) Implement proper URL key validation to prevent special characters, double hyphens, and excessively long slugs. (6) When changing URLs, always implement 301 redirects from old to new URLs.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'tech_http_headers_seo',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'technical_seo',
        'title'       => 'HTTP Headers for SEO - X-Robots-Tag, Link, Cache-Control',
        'tags'        => ['http-headers', 'x-robots-tag', 'link-header', 'cache-control', 'server-config'],
        'content'     => 'HTTP response headers provide SEO directives at the server level, complementing or replacing HTML meta tags. They are particularly useful for non-HTML resources (PDFs, images) and for applying directives without modifying page content. X-Robots-Tag: applies robots directives via HTTP header. Supports all directives available in the robots meta tag. Examples: X-Robots-Tag: noindex (prevent indexing), X-Robots-Tag: noindex, nofollow, X-Robots-Tag: max-snippet:150, max-image-preview:large, X-Robots-Tag: unavailable_after: 10 Apr 2026 00:00:00 GMT. For user-agent-specific directives: X-Robots-Tag: googlebot: noindex. Use cases: (1) Prevent PDF indexing: apply X-Robots-Tag: noindex to PDF files in your server config. (2) Block staging environments: apply X-Robots-Tag: noindex, nofollow to all pages on staging.example.com. (3) Control image indexing: X-Robots-Tag: noimageindex on image file responses. Link header: provides link relationships via HTTP. Primary SEO use: Link: <https://example.com/product>; rel="canonical" delivers the canonical URL as a header, useful for non-HTML content. Also supports: Link: <https://example.com/de/product>; rel="alternate"; hreflang="de" for hreflang annotations on non-HTML resources. Cache-Control: while not a direct SEO signal, proper caching improves page speed and reduces server load, both of which impact SEO. Recommended settings: static assets (CSS, JS, images): Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable (use versioned filenames for cache busting). HTML pages: Cache-Control: public, max-age=0, must-revalidate (or use Varnish for full page caching with appropriate TTL). API responses: Cache-Control: private, no-cache. Additional important headers: (1) Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains; preload (HSTS, forces HTTPS). (2) X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff (prevents MIME type sniffing). (3) Referrer-Policy: strict-origin-when-cross-origin (controls referrer information sent to other sites). (4) Permissions-Policy: camera=(), microphone=(), geolocation=() (restricts browser feature access). For Magento, configure these headers in nginx/Apache config or via a Magento module that adds headers to all responses.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'tech_redirects_301_302',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'technical_seo',
        'title'       => '301 vs 302 Redirects',
        'tags'        => ['redirects', '301', '302', 'url-migration', 'link-equity'],
        'content'     => 'Redirects tell search engines and browsers that a page has moved to a new URL. The choice between 301 and 302 affects how Google handles link equity, indexing, and URL canonicalization. 301 (Permanent Redirect): signals that the page has permanently moved. Google transfers nearly 100% of link equity (PageRank) from the old URL to the new URL (Google confirmed in 2016 that 301, 302, and 307 all pass full PageRank, but 301 is still the clearest signal for permanent moves). Google replaces the old URL with the new URL in its index. Use 301 when: (1) You have permanently changed a URL slug. (2) You are migrating to a new domain. (3) You are consolidating duplicate pages. (4) You have removed a product and redirecting to a relevant category or replacement. (5) You are changing URL structure (e.g., removing .html suffix). 302 (Temporary Redirect): signals that the page has temporarily moved. Google may keep the original URL in the index rather than replacing it with the redirect target. Use 302 when: (1) A product is temporarily out of stock and you are redirecting to an alternative. (2) You are A/B testing different URLs. (3) You are doing temporary maintenance on a page. (4) You are redirecting users based on geolocation (with proper Vary headers). (5) A seasonal page is temporarily redirecting to a related page until the season returns. Other redirect codes: 307 (Temporary, preserves HTTP method) is the HTTP/1.1 equivalent of 302. 308 (Permanent, preserves HTTP method) is the HTTP/1.1 equivalent of 301. Implementation in Magento: (1) Use Magento\'s URL Rewrite management (Marketing > URL Rewrites) for individual redirects. (2) For bulk redirects during migration, use server-level redirects in nginx/Apache config for better performance. (3) Monitor redirect performance: each redirect adds 50-100ms of latency. (4) Clean up old redirects periodically. If the old URL receives no traffic and has no external links, the redirect can be removed after 1-2 years. (5) Always redirect HTTP to HTTPS and non-www to www (or vice versa) using 301 at the server level, not via Magento.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'tech_redirect_chains_loops',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'technical_seo',
        'title'       => 'Redirect Chains and Loops',
        'tags'        => ['redirect-chains', 'redirect-loops', 'crawl-budget', 'technical-issues'],
        'content'     => 'Redirect chains occur when URL A redirects to URL B, which redirects to URL C (or further). Redirect loops occur when URL A redirects to URL B, which redirects back to URL A (creating an infinite cycle). Both are serious technical SEO problems. Redirect chains impact: (1) Each hop in a chain adds 50-100ms of latency. A 3-hop chain adds 150-300ms before the user sees any content. (2) Google follows up to 10 redirects in a chain but may stop earlier if the chain is excessively long or slow. Googlebot has a limited crawl budget, and chains waste it. (3) While Google says PageRank passes through redirect chains, each hop introduces a small risk of equity loss, especially if some hops use 302 instead of 301. (4) Chains complicate debugging and maintenance. Common causes in Magento: (1) HTTP > HTTPS > www normalization creating 2 hops: http://example.com > https://example.com > https://www.example.com. Fix by redirecting directly: http://example.com > https://www.example.com. (2) URL rewrite stacking: product URL changes from /old-name to /new-name to /newest-name. Each change adds a redirect through Magento\'s URL rewrite table. Fix by updating old redirects to point directly to the final URL. (3) Trailing slash inconsistency: /category redirects to /category/ which then redirects for another reason. Redirect loops causes: (1) Conflicting redirect rules: an htaccess rule redirects /page to /new-page, but a Magento URL rewrite redirects /new-page back to /page. (2) Circular canonical + redirect configurations. (3) CDN or load balancer redirect conflicts with server-level redirects. Detection and resolution: (1) Use Screaming Frog or Sitebulb to crawl your site and identify chains longer than 1 hop and any loops. (2) In Magento admin, audit the url_rewrite database table for chains: SELECT * FROM url_rewrite WHERE target_path IN (SELECT request_path FROM url_rewrite WHERE redirect_type > 0). (3) Fix chains by updating all intermediate redirects to point directly to the final destination. (4) Fix loops by identifying and removing the conflicting rule. (5) Test with curl -L -v to trace the full redirect path. (6) Monitor Search Console for "Redirect error" in the Pages indexing report. (7) Implement automated monitoring to detect new chains after content changes.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'tech_soft_404',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'technical_seo',
        'title'       => 'Soft 404 Detection and Resolution',
        'tags'        => ['soft-404', '404', 'error-pages', 'indexing', 'crawl-quality'],
        'content'     => 'A soft 404 occurs when a page returns a 200 HTTP status code but displays content that indicates the page does not exist or has no meaningful content. Google\'s algorithms detect soft 404s and treat them as true 404s for indexing purposes, but they waste crawl budget because Google must download and render the full page to detect the pattern. Common soft 404 scenarios in Magento: (1) Out-of-stock products displaying an empty page or "product not available" message with a 200 status. (2) Category pages with zero products after filtering, showing "no results found" with a 200 status. (3) Search results pages for queries with no matches. (4) CMS pages with placeholder content or "coming soon" text. (5) Paginated category pages beyond the actual number of pages (e.g., /category?p=999 returning an empty listing). Detection: Google Search Console reports soft 404s in the Pages > Not indexed > "Soft 404" section. Review these URLs to understand the pattern. Resolution strategies: (1) Return a proper 410 (Gone) status for permanently removed products. 410 tells Google the page is intentionally removed and will not return, causing faster deindexing than 404. Configure Magento to return 410 for disabled/deleted products. (2) Return 404 for pages that never existed or were removed but might return. (3) For temporarily out-of-stock products, keep the page live with a 200 status, display "out of stock" clearly, offer alternatives or notify-when-available functionality, and maintain the product schema with availability set to OutOfStock. This preserves SEO value. (4) For empty category pages after filtering, either prevent indexing with noindex or ensure the page still provides value (show related products, parent category content). (5) For paginated pages beyond the last page, return 404 instead of an empty listing. (6) Customize the 404 page to be helpful: include search functionality, popular categories, and recent products. A useful 404 page reduces bounce rate when users land on removed pages from external links. (7) Monitor soft 404s weekly in Search Console and address patterns systemically rather than page by page.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'tech_pagination_seo',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'technical_seo',
        'title'       => 'Pagination SEO - rel=prev/next Deprecated, Alternatives',
        'tags'        => ['pagination', 'category-pages', 'rel-prev-next', 'infinite-scroll', 'load-more'],
        'content'     => 'Google officially announced in March 2019 that it had not used rel="prev" and rel="next" as an indexing signal for several years. This means paginated pages are treated as individual standalone pages by Google. Current best practices for pagination SEO in 2026: (1) Self-referencing canonicals on each paginated page. Page 2 should canonical to itself (/category?p=2), NOT to page 1. Canonicalizing all pages to page 1 hides products on pages 2+ from Google entirely. (2) Allow Google to crawl all paginated pages. Do not noindex paginated pages if they contain unique products that are not accessible elsewhere. The products on page 5 of a category need to be discoverable. (3) Create a "view all" page if feasible (under 200 products). A single page listing all products consolidates link equity and ensures every product is discoverable. Set this as the canonical if you implement it. For categories with hundreds of products, this may not be practical due to page weight. (4) Use HTML links for pagination navigation, not JavaScript-only buttons. Googlebot must be able to follow pagination links to discover all pages. <a href="/category?p=2">Next</a> works; a JavaScript click handler that updates content via AJAX does not. (5) Include self-referencing canonical URLs with full query parameters: <link rel="canonical" href="https://example.com/category?p=2" />. (6) Ensure the XML sitemap includes all product pages regardless of which paginated page they appear on. This provides an alternate discovery path. (7) For infinite scroll or load-more patterns, implement the hybrid approach: maintain real paginated URLs (/category?p=1, /category?p=2) that work as standalone pages with proper HTML. Layer infinite scroll or load-more JavaScript on top for the user experience. Use replaceState/pushState to update the URL as the user scrolls, so Google can crawl the underlying paginated HTML structure. (8) Internal linking to products deep in pagination should occur through non-paginated paths (related products, blog links, footer featured products) to ensure discoverability without relying solely on pagination crawling.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'tech_international_seo',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'technical_seo',
        'title'       => 'International SEO - Hreflang, ccTLD vs Subdomain vs Subdirectory',
        'tags'        => ['international-seo', 'hreflang', 'cctld', 'subdomain', 'subdirectory', 'multilingual'],
        'content'     => 'International SEO involves serving the right content to users based on their language and/or location. The three primary URL structure approaches each have distinct trade-offs. (1) Country-code top-level domains (ccTLDs): example.de, example.fr, example.co.uk. Advantages: strongest geo-targeting signal, clear brand localization, independent authority building per market. Disadvantages: highest cost (domain registration, hosting, maintenance per domain), link equity is not shared across domains, each domain starts with zero authority. Best for: large enterprises with dedicated teams and budgets per market. (2) Subdomains: de.example.com, fr.example.com. Advantages: moderate geo-targeting signal (configurable in Search Console), easier to set up than separate domains, can be hosted on different servers. Disadvantages: subdomains are treated as semi-separate entities by Google, link equity sharing is limited. Best for: organizations needing independent technical infrastructure per market. (3) Subdirectories: example.com/de/, example.com/fr/. Advantages: all link equity consolidates on a single domain, simplest to maintain, single SSL certificate, single hosting infrastructure. Disadvantages: weaker geo-targeting signal (configurable in Search Console), requires single hosting infrastructure for all markets. Best for: most businesses, especially ecommerce. This is the recommended default approach in 2026. Magento multistore configuration: Magento supports all three approaches through its multistore architecture. Subdirectory is most common: create separate store views for each language/region, configure base URLs as /en/, /de/, /fr/. Implementation checklist: (1) Implement hreflang annotations on every page (see hreflang entry). (2) Translate all content, including meta tags, alt text, structured data, and URL slugs. Machine translation without review is detectable and harmful. (3) Use the correct currency and measurement units for each market. (4) Localize product availability and pricing per market. (5) Set geographic targeting in Google Search Console for subdirectories and subdomains. (6) Host servers close to target markets or use a global CDN. (7) Build local backlinks in each target market. (8) Submit localized sitemaps per market. (9) Handle content that does not exist in all languages: use x-default to direct users to the most appropriate available version, or return a language selection page.',
    ],

    [
        'id'          => 'tech_log_file_analysis',
        'category'    => 'seo',
        'subcategory' => 'technical_seo',
        'title'       => 'Log File Analysis for SEO',
        'tags'        => ['log-files', 'server-logs', 'crawl-analysis', 'googlebot', 'crawl-budget'],
        'content'     => 'Log file analysis reveals exactly how search engine crawlers interact with your site, providing insights that no other SEO tool can offer. While Search Console shows what Google indexed, log files show what Google actually crawled, including pages it visited but chose not to index. What to analyze: (1) Crawl frequency: how often does Googlebot visit each page? High-value pages should be crawled daily. If important product pages are crawled monthly, there is a crawl budget allocation problem. (2) Crawl budget waste: identify URLs receiving significant Googlebot traffic that should not be crawled. Common waste: filtered URLs with parameters, internal search result pages, shopping cart and checkout pages, faceted navigation permutations, and paginated pages deep in a series. (3) Status code distribution: track 200, 301, 302, 404, 410, 500 responses to Googlebot. A spike in 5xx errors indicates server issues affecting crawling. (4) Response time: measure server response time for Googlebot requests. Consistently slow responses (over 500ms) cause Googlebot to reduce crawl rate. (5) Crawl patterns: identify which times Googlebot crawls most actively and whether it follows expected paths through your site structure. (6) New page discovery: measure the time between publishing a new page and Googlebot\'s first visit. Implementation: (1) Access web server logs (nginx access.log, Apache access.log). Filter for Googlebot user agent: "Mozilla/5.0 (compatible; Googlebot/2.1; +http://www.google.com/bot.html)" and "Mozilla/5.0 AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko; compatible; Googlebot/2.1; +http://www.google.com/bot.html) Chrome/W.X.Y.Z Safari/537.36". (2) Verify genuine Googlebot via reverse DNS: the IP should resolve to *.googlebot.com or *.google.com. (3) Use tools: Screaming Frog Log File Analyzer, Botify, JetOctopus, or Oncrawl for automated analysis. For manual analysis, use ELK stack (Elasticsearch, Logstash, Kibana) or custom scripts. Key Magento insights from log analysis: (1) Identify if Googlebot is wasting crawls on layered navigation URLs (/category?color=red&size=m&price=50-100). If so, block the parameter patterns in robots.txt or add noindex. (2) Confirm that XML sitemap URLs are actually being crawled. (3) Detect if Googlebot is encountering errors on critical pages that are not visible in Search Console. (4) Measure the impact of technical changes on crawl behavior. (5) Run log analysis monthly at minimum, weekly during site migrations or major changes.',
    ],
];
